'''Edgar Ricardo Arjona Morales''', (born 19 January 1964, in [[Jocotenango]], [[Guatemala]]), known as '''Ricardo Arjona''' ({{IPA-es|ar<U+02C8>xona}}), is a Guatemalan [[singer-songwriter]] and former [[basketball player]] and [[school teacher]]. Arjona is one of the most successful Latin American artists of all time, with more than 20 million albums sold to date.<ref>(6 April 2012). [http://www.webcitation.org/67nxjOrUm "Con la presentaci<U+00F3>n de "Independiente", Ricardo Arjona volver<U+00E1> ma<U+00F1>ana a C<U+00F3>rdoba"] (in Spanish). Cadena 3. Archived from [http://www.cadena3.com/contenido/2012/04/06/95001.asp the original]. Retrieved on 7 April 2012.
*[http://www.webcitation.org/67nxqh1SR "Ricardo Arjona sale a la cancha de Newell's con su equipo rom<U+00E1>ntico"]. La Capital (Argentina). Archived from[http://www.lacapital.com.ar/escenario/Ricardo-Arjona-sale-a-la-cancha-de-Newells-con-su-equipo-romantico-20120410-0009.htmlthe original]. Retrieved on April 18, 2012.</ref> He is often called ''El Animal Nocturno'' (''The Nocturnal Animal''),<ref name="Moscatel">Moscatel, Susana (23 March 2012). [http://www.webcitation.org/67nxuhUmC "Ahmadineyad vs. Arjona"]. Milenio. Archived from [http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/impreso/9134034 the original]. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> thanks to his breakthrough success with his fourth studio album which [[Animal Nocturno|bears the same name]]. His music ranges from [[ballad]]s to [[Latin pop]], rock, [[pop rock]], [[Cuban music]], and more recently [[A capella|a cappella performances]] and a mixture of [[Tejano music]] and [[Norte<U+00F1>o (music)|Norte<U+00F1>o music]], and other [[Afro-American music|Afro-American]] and [[Latin music|Latin sounds]]. Arjona is noted for his lyrical style, and often addresses topics such as love, homosexuality, [[kidnapping]], [[rape]], [[Racism|interracial racism]] and immigration.

As of 2011, Arjona had released thirteen studio albums, one live album, nine [[compilation albums]] and forty-three singles. Four Arjona albums reached number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]], and ten reached number 1 in [[Argentina]]. Four albums had charted on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. Four singles had reached Number 1 on the [[Billboard Latin Songs|''Billboard'' Latin Songs]] chart and seven had done the same on [[Latin Pop Songs]]. His work earned him numerous awards and accolades, including one [[Grammy Award]], one [[Latin Grammy Award]], the "Latin Heritage" Award<ref>[http://www.webcitation.org/67ny1XeH8 "14th Annual El Premio ASCAP 2006 <U+2013> ASCAP Latin Heritage Award honoring Ricardo Arjona"]. [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]]. Archived from[http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/latinawards/2006/heritage.html the original]. Retrieved on 24 March 2012.</ref> as well as awards from the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]]; a silver and golden torch and two silver seagulls from the [[2010 Vi<U+00F1>a del Mar International Song Festival]], two [[2010 Latin Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], and a "Latin Trajectory of the Year" Award at the Orgullosamente Latino Awards of 2010.

==Early years and personal life==
Edgar Ricardo Arjona Morales was born on 19 January 1964 in Jocotenango, Guatemala, to parents Ricardo Arjona Moscoso and Mimi Morales de Arjona. He lived most of his childhood and began his musical instruction in [[Guatemala City]].<ref name=adnradio>[http://www.adnradio.cl/noticia/ricardo-arjona/20081023/nota/696478.aspx]. ADN. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> At the age of eight, young Ricardo could already play the guitar.<ref name=terra1/> At age twelve, he participated in the contest "Festival Infantil Juventud 74" with "Gracias al Mundo", a song composed by his father, finally winning the event.<ref>[http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-686145 "Los colapsos emocionales de Arjona"]. [[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]. Retrieved on 19 May 2012.</ref>

Although he initially enrolled in architecture and engineering, he graduated with a degree from the School of Communication Sciences at the [[Universidad de San Carlos de Guatemala]] (USAC).<ref name=cosme>Cosme, Hector.[http://www.periodicolaperla.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2150:ricardo-arjona-de-guatemala-para-el-mundo&catid=119:articulos&Itemid=342"Arjona: de Guatemala para el mundo"]. Periodico La Perla. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> Arjona was a talented basketball player who played for ''Leones de Marte'' and ''TRIAS''.<ref name=terra1>(12-10-2010). [http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloid=975400 "Biograf<U+00ED>a de Ricardo Arjona"].''Terra''. Retrieved 13 October 2011.</ref> He toured Central America as a member of the Guatemalan national team. Until recently, he held the record for the most points scored (78) in a single game by a Guatemalan.<ref name="B&T">{{cite news |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=TRMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Ricardo+Arjona#v=onepage&q=Ricardo%20Arjona&f=false |title=Arjona Innovates On CD/DVD Set|last=Cobo|first=Leiba |date=4 December 2004 |work=Billboard |page=23 |accessdate=6 July 2011}}
*[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ricardo-arjona-p37108/biography Ricardo Arjona]. [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved on 24 March 2012.</ref> He also taught at a primary school (called ''Santa Elena III''),<ref name=cosme/> where he claimed to have spent six hours giving lessons and the rest of the day playing soccer.<ref name="B&T"/> This earned him a visit from a Ministry of Education representative, who was sent to evaluate his pupils. The representative found that the students' education was actually above average.<ref name="Biograf<U+00ED>a de Ricardo Arjona"/> 

In the city of [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, he met [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] Leslie Torres and had two children with her: Adria and Ricardo. They separated in 2005. As of 2010, Arjona was dating [[Venezuelan]] model Daisy Arvelo, with whom he has a child.<ref>[http://www.analitica.com/va/entretenimiento/quepasa/9652346.asp "La modelo venezolana Daisy Arvelo est<U+00E1> embarazada de Ricardo Arjona"]. Analitica.com. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref>

==Career==

====1980s: Beginnings and early breakthrough====
Arjona began his musical career at age 21,<ref name="terra1"/> when he signed with record label PolyGram<ref>(26-09-2011). [http://www.emol.com/noticias/magazine/2011/09/26/505071/las-razones-de-la-independencia-de-arjona.html "Arjona desclasifica los episodios menos glamorosos de su paso por las discogr<U+00E1>ficas"]. ''Emol.com''. Retrieved 15 October 2011.</ref> and released his debut album ''[[D<U+00E9>jame Decir Que Te Amo]]'' in 1985. The label attempted to portray Arjona as a stereotypical Latin-lover.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/arjona_ricardo/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd Ricardo Arjona]. MTV.com (US). Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> The title track was released as a single, "D<U+00E9>jame Decir Que Te Amo". This album failed to chart, but received moderate critical success, with [[Allmusic]] awarding it 3 stars out of five.<ref name="Allmusic">[http://allmusic.com/album/dejame-decir-que-te-amo-r236313 Allmusic Review] accessed 23 August 2011</ref> Because of his negative experience recording the album and its commercial failure, he decided to abandon music to teach school.<ref name=cosme/>

At age 24, Arjona reversed himself and sought the opportunity to represent his country on the [[OTI Festival]] with the song "Con Una Estrella En El Vientre".<ref name=cosme/> The sessions immediately following this decision produced the song "S.O.S Resc<U+00E1>tame".<ref name=adnradio/> His second studio album, ''[[Jes<U+00FA>s, Verbo No Sustantivo]]'' brought him commercial and critical success over Latin America and the U.S. and became a best-seller in many Central American territories.<ref name=adnradio/><ref name=cosme/>

====1990s: International breakthrough, ''Si El Norte Fuera El Sur'' and ''Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros''====
Arjona started the new decade known throughout Latin America. After joining [[Sony Music]] in 1990 he released ''[[Del Otro Lado del Sol]]'',<ref name=terra1/> one of his least successful. That year he started composing songs for other artists, such as [[Yuri (Mexican singer)|Yuri]]'s "Detr<U+00E1>s De Mi Ventana", for her album ''[[Nueva era]]'' (1993). The song became a hit, reaching #1 on the US Hot Latin Songs chart for three weeks in 1994.<ref name=DTMV-HLS>{{cite web|title=Top Latin Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/latin-songs#/charts/latin-songs?chartDate=1994-01-29|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=6 June 2012|location=United States|date=29 January 1994}}</ref><ref name=Billboard-29-01-1994>{{cite web|last=Lannert|first=John|title=Latin Notas|url=http://books.google.co.ve/books?id=HQgEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&pg=PA36|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=6 June 2012|location=United States|page=36|date=29 January 1994}}</ref> He later covered the song on his compilation album, ''[[Tr<U+00F3>pico]]'' (2009), alongside [[Melina Le<U+00F3>n]]. ''Animal Nocturno'', Arjona's fourth studio album, was released in 1993. The album sold 500,000 copies in 1994,<ref name=Lannert>{{cite web|last=Lannert|first=John|title=Pop Rockeros Rules: PolyGram's Pop Rock Rush|url=http://books.google.co.ve/books?id=aggEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=3 June 2012|location=United States|page=68|date=26 November 1994|quote=The Guatemalan native sold 500,000 units of his 1992 label debut, "Animal Nocturno."}}</ref> and carried him to fame/<ref name=animal1>(17-04-2009). [http://www.listindiario.com.do/entretenimiento/2009/4/16/97979/Arjona-queda-confirmado "Arjona queda confirmado"]. ''List<U+00ED>n Diario''. Retrieved 13 October 2011.</ref><ref name=animal2>[http://www.emol.com/noticias/magazine/2011/09/26/505071/las-razones-de-la-independencia-de-arjona.html "Arjona desclasifica los episodios menos glamorosos de su paso por las discogr<U+00E1>ficas"]. ''emol.com''. Retrieved 5 October 2011.</ref> His work on the Mexican [[telenovela]] ''Alcanzar Una Estrella'', showcased his songwriting and singing skills.<ref name=adnradio/> The album contained the hit singles "Mujeres" (#6 on Latin Songs) and "Primera Vez" (#6 on Latin Songs)<ref name="TLS"/> and received thirteen platinum and one diamond certifications.<ref name="Terra_Tiempos">[http://www.terra.com/musica/noticias/ricardo_arjona_el_canta_autor_de_los_tiempos/oci66221 "Ricardo Arjona, el canta autor de los tiempos"]. Terra (Terra Networks, S.A.)(in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]). Retrieved on 19 May 2012.</ref> 

He confirmed his reputation with the release of his fifth studio album, ''[[Historias]]''. The album sold 2 million copies throughout Latin America and received twenty-seven platinum and two diamond certifications,<ref name=terra1/> including quadruple Platinum in [[Argentina]].<ref name="capif"/> ''Historias'' reached #43 on Top Latin Albums.<ref name="TLA"/> Hit singles included "Te Conozco" (#3 on [[Billboard Latin Songs|''Billboard'' Latin Songs]]) and "Se<U+00F1>ora De Las Cuatro D<U+00E9>cadas" (#7 on Latin Songs).<ref name="TLS"/> The Allmusic review by Jason Birchmeier awarded the album 4.5 stars stating that "If you were to pick only one Arjona album for your collection that wasn't a greatest-hits [[Compilation album|compilation]], this should be the one. ''Historias'' was a career-defining success for Arjona."<ref name="Allmusic">Birchmeier, J. [http://allmusic.com/album/historias-r203600/review Allmusic Review] accessed 1 September 2011</ref> His fourth and fifth studio albums were the best-selling of his career.<ref name=Milenio>{{cite web|title=Alista Ricardo Arjona lanzamiento de su nuevo disco "Independiente"|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/5b3f6569861bc7b1ebc8edca2e00a13e|work=Milenio Online|publisher=Grupo Milenio|accessdate=5 October 2011|location=Mexico|language=Spanish|date=25 September 2011}}</ref><ref name="EMOL">{{cite web|title=Arjona desclasifica los episodios menos glamorosos de su paso por las discogr<U+00E1>ficas|url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/magazine/detalle/detallenoticias.asp?idnoticia=505071|work=El Mercurio Online|publisher=Empresas El Mercurio|accessdate=5 October 2011|location=Chile|language=Spanish|date=26 September 2011}}</ref>

In 1996, he released his sixth studio album, ''[[Si El Norte Fuera El Sur]]''. This was the first album in which Arjona ventured beyond the theme of love to explore nationalism and [[globalization]], among other sociopolitical topics.<ref name="The Romantic">{{cite web|last=Lannert|first=John|title=Arjona, The Romantic|url=http://books.google.co.ve/books?id=QQ0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es|date=16 May 1998|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=3 June 2012|location=United States|page=45}}</ref> Its four singles were "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur" (#9 on Latin Pop Songs),<ref name="LPS"/> whose main theme is the relationship between the United States and Latin America,<ref name="Billboard-03-05-1997"/> "Tu Reputaci<U+00F3>n" (#18 on Latin Songs, #2 on Latin Pop Songs), "Me Ense<U+00F1>aste" (#18 on Latin Pop Songs), and "Ella y <U+00C9>l" (#24 on Latin Songs, #8 on Latin Pop Songs).<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> Birchmeier awarded the album 4.5 stars stating "All in all, it's Arjona's third classic album in a row, each distinct from its predecessor."<ref name="Allmusic">Birchmeier, J. [http://allmusic.com/album/si-el-norte-fuera-el-sur-r263457/review Allmusic Review] accessed 1 September 2011</ref> ''Billboard'' named it the Rock Album of the Year in 1997.<ref name="Billboard-03-05-1997">{{cite web|last=Lannert|first=John|title=The Winners Are...|url=http://books.google.co.ve/books?id=IQ8EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&pg=PA28|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=3 June 2012|location=United States|page=28|date=3 May 1997}}</ref> ''Si El Norte Fuera El Sur'' received multiple [[Platinum certification]]s in the United States<ref name="riaa">{{Certification Cite|region=United States|artist="Arjona, Ricardo"|Spanish=yes|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref> and Argentina.<ref name="capif">{{Certification Cite|region=Argentina|artist=Ricardo Arjona|accessdate=24 June 2011}}{{dead link|date=April 2012}}</ref> 

In 1998, he released his seventh studio album, ''[[Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros]]''. Terry Jenkins Allmusic review awarded the album 4 stars stating "''Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros'' continues Ricardo Arjona's streak of accomplished, affecting albums that spotlights both his melodic skills and his sharp social consciousness."<ref name="Allmusic">Jenkins, T. [http://allmusic.com/album/sin-daos-a-terceros-r354616/review Allmusic Review] accessed 2 September 2011</ref> His fourth consecutive album to receive critical success, ''Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros'' also enjoyed commercial success, debuting at #6 on Top Latin Albums, the first to reach the top 10.<ref name="TLA"/> It also reached #3 on the [[Latin Pop Albums|''Billboard'' Latin Pop Albums]] chart.<ref name="LPA"/> It contained the hit singles "Dime Que No" (#6 on Latin Songs, #3 on Latin Pop Songs), and "Mentiroso" (#22 on Latin Songs, #5 on Latin Pop Songs).<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> The album received multiple Platinum certifications from the United States<ref name="riaa"/> and Argentina.<ref name="capif"/> More than 700,000 copies were sold.<ref name="Merit"/> 

On 5 December 1998 and in front of a live audience of more than 100,000 people at the [[Hippodrome]] of [[Guatemala City]], Arjona recorded his first live album, the 1999 release ''[[Vivo (Ricardo Arjona album)|Vivo]]''.<ref name="Terra_Tiempos"/> The album was moderately successful, certified Gold in [[Mexico]] and Platinum in the United States and Argentina. It produced the hit "Desnuda", which became his first #1 on Top Latin Songs.<ref name="TLS"/> As of December 2005, ''Vivo'' had sold 243,000 copies in the United States, his best-selling album there as of that date.<ref name="Billboard 10-12-2005">{{cite web|last=Cobo|first=Leila|title=Arjona Tries New Approach For 10th Album|url=http://books.google.co.ve/books?id=ZxMEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&pg=PA42|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=5 June 2012|page=42|date=10 December 2005}}</ref>

====2000<U+2013>2005: ''Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe'', world tour, ''Santo Pecado'', hiatus and ''Adentro''====
Arjona's eighth studio album, ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]'' was preceded by the single "Cu<U+00E1>ndo", which became a commercial success and reached #1 on both Top Latin Songs and Latin Pop Songs.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> The singer commented that the album consumed twelve months and that before starting, "he had more friends."<ref name="cara_a_cara"/> He also mentioned he had "lived in love with Caribbean culture and music since my childhood."<ref name="cara_a_cara"/> Birchmeier awarded the album 3 stars stating "All in all, ''Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe'' is a curious entry in Arjona's catalog that most fans can overlook without missing much."<ref name="Allmusic">Birchmeier, J. [http://allmusic.com/album/galeria-caribe-r495348/review Allmusic Review] accessed 4 September 2011</ref> The album became his first to chart on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], peaking at #136, while charting at #1 on Top Latin Albums and Latin Pop Albums.<ref name="TLA"/><ref name="LPA"/><ref name="BB200"/> It was awarded Platinum certification in Mexico,<ref name="amprofon">{{Certification Cite|region=Mexico|artist=Ricardo Arjona|accessdate=24 June 2011}}</ref> Argentina<ref name="capif"/> and the US.<ref name="riaa"/> Its three singles were "Lo Poco Que Queda De Mi"; "Mes<U+00ED>as", which reached #19 on Top Latin Songs and #11 on the Latin Pop Songs chart; and "A Cara O Cruz", which reached #28 on Latin Pop Songs.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> To promote the album, which sold more than one million copies, Arjona embarked on his ''Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe Tour'', which began in Mexico in 2000 and finished in 2001.<ref name="cara_a_cara">[http://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/2001/10/4/ESCENARIOS/escen5.html "Cara a cara con el Caribe"]. El Salvador.com. [[El Diario de Hoy]]. Retrieved on 19 May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.mi2n.com/press.php3?press_nb=17072 "Ricardo Arjona Launches His Tour, 'Galer<U+00ED>a Cairbe'"]. Music Industry News Network (MusicDish LLC.). Retrieved on 19 May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-1280125 "Arjona y su Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe"]. El Tiempo. Retrieved on 19 May 2012.</ref>

[[File:North face south tower after plane strike 9-11.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Fans and critics noted connections between the lyrics of "Mes<U+00ED>as" and the [[September 11 attacks]] on the [[World Trade Center]], resulting in an FBI investigation.]]
{{Listen
 |filename     = Arjona_Mesias.ogg
 |title        = "Mes<U+00ED>as"t
 |description  = A sample of "Mes<U+00ED>as", displaying the first chorus of the controversial song, investigated by the [[FBI]].<ref name="FBI"/>
}}
On "Mesias" Arjona talks about a character who appears "in the form of a wealthy, well-armed magnate with [...] some sinister plan for the world."<ref name="Gurza">Gurza, Agust<U+00ED>n (19 September 2001).[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/81448003.html?dids=81448003:81448003&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+19%2C+2001&author=AGUSTIN+GURZA&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Song%27s+Eerily+Prophetic+Lyrics+Have+Arjona%27s+Fans+Buzzing&pqatl=google "Song's Eerily Prophetic Lyrics Have Arjona's Fans Buzzing"]. [[Los Angeles Times]] (Archive). Pay-Per-View information, retrieved mainly on the resume page available on the PQ Archiver. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> Some critics argued that it was a "metaphorical attack" on [[capitalism]] and [[imperialism]], named as "classic Arjona targets."<ref name="Gurza"/> The song became a subject of some controversy when fans and critics noted connections between its theme and the [[9/11|attacks of September 2001]], months after the song's release, which resulted in the [[FBI]] investigating Arjona.<ref name="FBI">[http://archive.laprensa.com.sv/20011013/revista_eco/eco2.asp "Por su canci<U+00F3>n <U+201C>Mes<U+00ED>as<U+201D> Arjona fue investigado por el FBI"]. La Prensa (Archive). Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> The singer later commented that "Mes<U+00ED>as" had no relationship to the attacks, and that the lyrics were pure coincidence.<ref name="Perez">Perez, Juan Carlos (9 April 2007). [http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/81470/El+Mesias+es+pura+coincidencia.htm "'El Mes<U+00ED>as' es pura coincidencia"]. Terra. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> He further stated the FBI had never spoken directly to him, but instead to somebody on his team.<ref name="Perez"/> 

On 19 November 2002, Arjona released his ninth studio album, ''[[Santo Pecado]]'', preceded by singles "[[El Problema]]", which reached #1 on both the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Songs and Latin Pop Songs charts; and "[[Minutos]]" which reached #5 on the Top Latin Songs and #3 on the Latin Pop Songs charts.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> ''Santo Pecado'' became a commercial success, selling more than 300,000 copies just in Mexico (double Platinum),<ref name="amprofon"/> 160,000 in Argentina]] (quadruple Platinum)<ref name="capif"/> and 200,000 in the United States (double Platinum).<ref name="riaa"/>

In 2003 Arjona released ''[[Lados B]]'', his second compilation album, including songs that were "not so commercial", and that he wanted to give a second chance at radio airplay.<ref>[http://www.eluniverso.com/2003/12/20/0001/259/D259B7AD742149CB9A45C7E5AF7B1A9F.html "Ricardo Arjona lanz<U+00F3> disco con canciones que no tuvieron <U+00E9>xito"]. El Universo.</ref> The album contained songs from all his past studio albums. Critical reception for the album was mixed. Birchmeier noted that it was "a misleading entry point into Arjona's catalog."<ref name="Allmusic">Birchmeier, J. [http://allmusic.com/album/lados-b-r672095/review Allmusic Review] accessed 6 September 2011</ref> Despite this, the album received a Gold certification in Mexico.<ref name="amprofon"/>

On 6 December 2005, Arjona released his tenth studio album, ''[[Adentro]]''. This was Arjona's first collaboration with [[Tommy Torres]].<ref>[http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=12990 "Arjona ha vendido 500.000 copias de nuevo disco en Latinoam<U+00E9>rica"]. El Nuevo Diario. Retrieved on 25 March 2012.</ref> In an interview, the singer commented that he first "tested" Torres by sending him the "hookiest and darkest tracks" on the album, "[[Acompa<U+00F1>ame A Estar Solo]]" and "Iluso".<ref name="Billboard 10-12-2005"/> Torres said that he "went all out on the first demo, hiring a full band that included a string orchestra", which grabbed Arjona's attention.<ref name="Billboard 10-12-2005"/> The album was critically acclaimed, with Evan C. Gutierrez from Allmusic giving it four stars out of five and commenting that "Be it for the stripped, natural production value, the confident performance of Ricardo Arjona, or his relevant-as-ever [[Lyricist|lyricism]], he's got both his loyal fans and the execs at [[Sony Music Latin#Divisions|Norte]] smiling. While the instrumentation, performance, and overall sonic palette of this project are minimalist and unassuming, there is a depth and brilliance to them. The listener's ear does not tire or want for more, humble as ''Adentro'' is."<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/r808825 Adentro <U+2013> Ricardo Arjona]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> Arjona further commented that ''Adentro'' was "a very representative and tremendously complete album," adding that "having different producers made it rich in possibilities."<ref name="Billboard 10-12-2005"/>

''Adentro'' became Arjona's second studio album to chart on the Billboard 200, reaching #126.<ref name="BB200"/> It reached #3 on the Top Latin Albums and #2 on the Lain Pop Albums charts.<ref name="TLA"/><ref name="LPA"/> Five singles were released from ''Adentro'': the [[lead single]], "[[Acompa<U+00F1>ame A Estar Solo]]" (#7 on Latin Songs, #1 on Latin Pop Songs), "[[Ping<U+00FC>inos En La Cama]]" featuring Spanish singer [[Chenoa]] (#44 on Latin Songs, #19 on Latin Pop Songs); "[[Mojado (song)|Mojado]]", featuring American [[Tejano music|Tejano]]/[[Norte<U+00F1>o (music)|Norte<U+00F1>o]] band [[Intocable]] (#34 on Latin Songs, #30 on Latin Pop Songs), "[[A Ti]]" (#14 on Latin Songs, #3 on Latin Pop Songs) and "[[De Vez En Mes]]" (#49 on Latin Songs, #16 on Latin Pop Songs).<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> The album sold more than a million copies worldwide.<ref name=adentro1mill>[http://mensual.prensa.com/mensual/contenido/2006/02/23/hoy/vivir/511185.html "Arjona se considera <U+2018>un tipo de <U+00E9>xito<U+2019>"]. ''Prensa.com''. Retrieved 2 October 2011.</ref>

====2006<U+2013>2007: Adentro Tour and ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer''====
In 2006, Arjona started the first leg of his world tour, named the ''Adentro Tour''. The tour resumed in 2007 for a second leg, in which he visited more countries. Approximately, two million people attended the performances.<ref name="Biograf<U+00ED>a de Ricardo Arjona"/> The tour was officially closed on 14 September 2007 on the [[mainland]] city of [[Barquisimeto]], Venezuela, during the International Fair, in front of more than 100,000 people.<ref name="Biograf<U+00ED>a de Ricardo Arjona"/>

On 21 August 2007, Arjona released his fifth compilation album, ''[[Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer]]''. The album is a two-disc set which contains, on the first disc, new versions of past hits, some of them including featured artists such as [[Marta S<U+00E1>nchez]] on "Tarde (Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros)" from ''[[Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros]]''; [[Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3>]] on "Si El Norte Fuera el Sur", from [[Si El Norte Fuera El Sur|the album of the same name]]; [[Marc Anthony]] on "Historia de Taxi", from ''Historias''; [[Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica|Sandro]] on "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo", from ''Historias''; and [[Eros Ramazzotti]] on "A Ti", from ''[[Adentro]]''. The second disc contained remastered versions of the hits on the first disc, but in their original versions. It was the second time Arjona collaborated with Torres.

The album became a critical and commercial success, with a positive Birchmeier review, who commented that "while only a couple of the new versions depart stylistically from the originals, the contemporary productions breathe new life into these songs, which should be well known by longtime fans";<ref name="birchmeier">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1184550|pure_url=yes}}|title= Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer > Review| first=Jason|last=Birchmeier |publisher=Allmusic |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref> and reaching double Platinum in Argentina<ref name="capif"/> and the United States,<ref name="riaa"/> and Platinum in Mexico.<ref name="amprofon"/> Also, it went Gold in Colombia, [[Chile]] and [[Venezuela]].<ref name=adn1>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_dijo_ayer_tour_gira_co070907.html "Ricardo Arjona presenta `<U+00BF>Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer?' en Colombia y Venezuela"]. ''adnmundo.com''. Retrieved 3 October 2011.</ref> Two singles were released from the album. The first, "[[Qui<U+00E9>n]]", a previously unreleased song and one of those produced by Torres, failed to reach the top 20 on Latin Songs, standing at #21, but reaching #4 on the Latin Pop Songs chart.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> "[[Quiero (Ricardo Arjona song)|Quiero]]", the secong single, reached #12 on the Latin Songs chart, and #8 on the Latin Pop Songs chart.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/>

====2008<U+2013>2010: New label, ''Quinto Piso'', world tour and ''Poquita Ropa''====
[[File:Ricardo Arjona in Laredo Entertainment Center.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=A man standing in front of the audience while in the middle of a concert, surrounded by the apartment-styled scenography and the rest of the musicians.|Ricardo Arjona in [[Laredo, Texas]] during ''[[Quinto Piso Tour]]''.]]
After spending the majority of his career with Sony, and [[Sony BMG]], Arjona signed a long-term deal with [[Warner Music Latina]] in September 2008.<ref name=leila1>Cobo, Leila (22 September 2008). [http://www.billboard.com/news/ricardo-arjona-signs-with-warner-music-latina-1003853422.story#/news/ricardo-arjona-signs-with-warner-music-latina-1003853422.story "Ricardo Arjona Signs With Warner Music Latina"]. Billboard. retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref><ref name=leila1/> I<U+00F1>igo Zabala, chairman of Warner Music Latin America commented. "He's an artist that fits perfectly with our company," and that "We are a label that has a major catalog of songwriters and quality pop and rock from the likes of [[Man<U+00E1>]], [[Alejandro Sanz]], [[Laura Pausini]], and now, Arjona."<ref name=leila1/>

Arjona announced his eleventh studio album, ''[[5to Piso]]'', on 18 November 2008. The album was preceded by the first single, "[[Como Duele]]" on September, which reached #2 on Top Latin Songs and #1 on Latin Pop Songs.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/> He moved approximately 200,000 copies in the first month at retail and went Platinum in [[Mexico]],<ref name="amprofon"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.entretienes.com/internaCont_idc_297393_id_cat_250.html |title=Ricardo Arjona recibe disco de oro por ventas en M<U+00E9>xico |date=20 November 2008  |work=Entretienes.com |accessdate=10 April 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jornadanet.com/Hemeroteca/n.php?a=23751-1&f=20081120 "Ricardo Arjona recibe disco de oro por sus 50.000 copias vendidas en M<U+00E9>xico"]. ''JornadaNet.com''. Retrieved 1 October 2011.</ref> the United States,<ref name="riaa"/><ref>[http://www.eltiempo.com.ec/noticias-cuenca/10384-ricardo-arjona-recibe-disco-de-platino/ "Ricardo Arjona recibe Disco de Platino"]. ''eltiempo.com.ec''. Retrieved 1 October 2011.</ref> Spain, Argentina,<ref name="capif"/><ref>[http://www.estereofonica.com/ricardo-arjona-recibio-el-disco-triple-platino-y-sigue-su-gira-por-el-interior/ "Ricardo Arjona recibi<U+00F3> el disco triple platino y sigue su gira por el interior"]. ''EstereoFonica.com''. Retrieved 1 October 2011.</ref>Venezuela,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conciertos10.com/el-nuevo-disco-de-arjona-%E2%80%9C5to-piso%E2%80%9D-debuta-como-el-numero-1-en-usa/ |title=El nuevo disco de Arjona "5to. Piso" debuta como el n<U+00FA>mero 1 en USA |date=20 May 2009  |work=Conciertos10.com |accessdate=10 April 2011}}</ref> [[Colombia]], Guatemala, and several other countries.<ref name=Uni134>[http://musica.univision.com/noticias/article/2008-11-26/arjona-logro-estos-reconocimientos-por "Arjona logr<U+00F3> estos reconocimientos por las altas ventas que su nuevo disco."]. ''Univisi<U+00F3>n''. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref> It debuted at #1 on Top Latin Albums, becoming his second chart-topper on that list, and sold more than one million copies worldwide.<ref name="TLA"/><ref>[http://www.nacion.com/2010-07-29/Entretenimiento/UltimaHora/Entretenimiento2465948.aspx "Ricardo Arjona se pone tropical en su nuevo disco"]. La Naci<U+00F3>n. Retrieved on 11 May 2012.</ref> The album received a Grammy Award nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]] and a [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2009|Latin Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Singer-Songwriter Album|Best Singer-Songwriter Album]].<ref name=LatinGrammy2009>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com/musica/noticias/conoce_a_los_nominados_a_los_grammy_latinos/oci701873|title=Conoce a los nominados a los Grammy Latinos|publisher=Terra Networks M<U+00E9>xico|date=19 September 2009|accessdate=28 January 2011|page=2|language=Spanish}}</ref> The album received critical positive response. Birchmeier gave it three-and-a-half stars out of five, saying that "More typical than exceptional for Arjona at this point in his career, ''5to Piso'' isn't as grand an album as his past few, [...], Yet it's a great album all the same, particularly the opening run of songs that culminates with "[[Como Duele|C<U+00F3>mo Duele]]", and it finds Arjona still at the top of his craft."<ref name="birchmeier">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1446244|pure_url=yes}}|title= 5to Piso > Review| first=Jason|last=Birchmeier |publisher=Allmusic |accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref>

While [[Warner Music]] released his new studio album, [[Sony Music]] released a compilation album, ''[[Simplemente Lo Mejor]]''. This led to speculation that the labels were in a fight to win Arjona's fanbase and sales.<ref>(19 November 2008). [http://sonfamosos.com/2008/11/19/sony-bmg-y-warner-music-se-pelean-por-fans-de-ricardo-arjona/ "Sony BMG y Warner Music se pelean por fans de Ricardo Arjona"]. Son Famosos. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> ''Simplemente Lo Mejor'' contained hits from past albums, namely ''[[Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros]]'', ''[[Si El Norte Fuera El Sur]]'', among others. This compilation went Gold in Mexico,<ref name="amprofon"/> and Platinum in Argentina.<ref name="capif"/>

"[[Sin Ti... Sin Mi]]" was released as ''5to Piso'''s second single, and reached #4 on both Top Latin Songs and Latin Pop Songs charts. On 24 April 2009, Arjona started the [[Quinto Piso Tour]]. The tour included 123 shows in the United States,<ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/616290.html Arjona inicia gira en EU]. ''El Universal (Mexico)''. Retrieved 11 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref> Spain,<ref name=spain1>[http://www.eluniverso.com/2009/04/23/1/1378/CC0DD8B0685E48958E289BCABCC25513.html Arjona visita Espa<U+00F1>a para empezar gira promocional]. ''El Universal (Mexico)''. Retrieved 11 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref><ref>[http://www.latercera.com/contenido/724_121417_9.shtml Ricardo Arjona regresa a Espa<U+00F1>a "m<U+00E1>s maduro y evolucionado" con su nuevo <U+00E1>lbum]. ''[http://www.latercera.com/ La Tercera]''. Retrieved 11 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref>  Argentina,<ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/633310.html Ricardo Arjona lleva su gira a Argentina]. ''El Universal (Mexico)''. Retrieved 11 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref><ref name=argentina2>[http://www.rpp.com.pe/2009-11-12-ricardo-arjona-finalizo-con-gran-exito-gira-por-argentina-y-chile-noticia_222131.html Ricardo Arjona finaliz<U+00F3> con gran <U+00E9>xito gira por Argentina y Chile]. ''RPP Per<U+00FA>''. Retrieved 11 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref> Guatemala, Colombia, Venezuela and Mexico, among many other countries in Latin America, and ended on 18 June 2010. 

{{Quote box
| quote  = In a discussion regarding theme of "Puente", Arjona commented: "Although many believe is a treshed topic, it isn't for a cuban, be it on [[Cuba|the island]] or [[Florida]]. The status of this dispute hasn't changed since 1959 and i've never seen something as disgusting as a rivality between people occasionated from politics. [[Hugo Ch<U+00E1>vez|Ch<U+00E1>vez]] can fight with [[<U+00C1>lvaro Uribe|Uribe]], [[Fidel Castro|Fidel]] with [[Barack Obama|Obama]], but what has this to do with two third-generation cousins that inherit an enmity for a politic matter[?]".
:<U+2014>Ricardo Arjona.<ref name="Arjona-Puente"/>
| width  = 25em
| align  = left
| quoted = 1
}}
The ''Quinto Piso Tour'' was one of the most successful tours made by a Latin artist, with more than one million attendees from 19 countries.<ref name=prensalibre1>[http://www.prensalibre.com/escenario/espectaculos/Ricardo-Arjona-Quinto-Piso-Guatemala_0_277772478.html Ricardo Arjona cerrar<U+00E1> su gira Quinto Piso en Guatemala]. ''Prensa Libre''. Retrieved 15 September 2011 (Spanish)</ref> He received in 2010 the "Latin Tour of the Year" [[2010 Latin Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Award]] for the tour.<ref name=prensalibre1/> On 26 February 2010, he participated in the [[2010 Vi<U+00F1>a del Mar International Song Festival]] as one of the top performers.<ref>[http://www.elparadiario14.cl/admin/render/noticia/18636 "Festival de Vi<U+00F1>a 2010: Ricardo Arjona es el nuevo confirmado"].  El Paradiario 14. Retrieved on 29 March 2012.</ref> His performance was followed by Colombian singer [[Fanny Lu]]. One hour after Lu's performance, a [[2010 Chile earthquake|8.8 magnitude massive earthquake]] affected the south-central regions of Chile. On [[social networks]], Arjona was jokingly blamed, with remarks such as "earthquakes go where he goes", making reference also to the [[2010 Mexican earthquake|earthquake felt in Mexico]] after the singer arrived.<ref>Notimex (21 March 2012). [http://www.laopinion.com/article/20120322/ENTRETENIMIENTO03/303229896/-1/ENTRETENIMIENTO "Redes sociales 'culpan' a Arjona del terremoto"]. La Opini<U+00F3>n. Retrieved on 29 March 2012.</ref><ref name=laextra>(24 March 2012). [http://laextra.mx/arjona-es-blanco-de-bromas-en-redes-sociales-por-culpa-de-terremotos/ "Arjona es blanco de bromas en redes sociales por culpa de terremotos"]. La Extra (M<U+00E9>xico). Retrieved on 29 March 2012.</ref>

After the tour, Arjona announced his twelfth studio album, ''[[Poquita Ropa]]'', which was released on 24 August 2010.<ref>[http://elnuevodiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=207733 "Ricardo Arjona lanza en agosto su nuevo disco, Poquita Ropa"]. El Nuevo Diario. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> It was preceded by the genre-mixing track "[[Puente (song)|Puente]]", an ode to [[Havana]], Cuba's largest and capital city.<ref name="Arjona-Puente">[http://www.elcolombiano.com/BancoConocimiento/A/arjona_canta_ahora_con_poquita_ropa/arjona_canta_ahora_con_poquita_ropa.asp "Arjona canta ahora con poquita ropa"]. Elcolombiano.com. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> The song failed to break in the upper tier of ''Billboard'' charts, and was reportedly prohibited in Cuba.<ref>Milan<U+00E9>s Despaigne, Jorge (February 2, 2011). [http://www.havanatimes.org/sp/?p=12625 "Vamos a hacer un puente"]. Havana Times. Retrieved on April 23, 2012.</ref> The album became his third to debut or reach #1 on the Top Latin Albums chart.<ref name="TLA"/> Within two weeks of release, the album received a Gold certification in Chile, United States, Colombia and [[Puerto Rico]]; and Platinum certification in Mexico and Argentina.<ref>[http://www.informador.com.mx/entretenimiento/2010/230567/6/debuta-ricardo-arjona-en-listas-de-ventas-de-eu.htm Debuta Ricardo Arjona en listas de ventas de EU]. Spanish</ref> 

The album marked a change in Arjona's sound, which himself called a "stripped-down version" of his music.<ref name=unionradio1>[http://www.unionradio.net/ActualidadUR/Nota/visorNota.aspx?id=52024&tpCont=1 "Arjona desnuda sus canciones en "Poquita ropa""]. Union Radio. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> Birchmeier gave the album a somewhat positive review, saying that it was a "stripped-down acoustic effort" yet considering it "impressive".<ref name="birchmeier"/> Two more singles were released from ''Poquita Ropa'', "[[Vida (song)|Vida]]", a song the singer dedicated to his recently dead father;<ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com/2010/11/17/til_ava_recuerda-ricardo-arj_17A4744331.shtml "Recuerda Ricardo Arjona a su padre en tema autobiogr<U+00E1>fico"]. El Universal (Venezuela). Retrieved on march 23, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.el-carabobeno.com/portada/articulo/3875/ricardo-arjona-lanza-su-sencillo-vida "Ricardo Arjona lanza su sencillo <U+201C>Vida<U+201D>"]. El Carabobe<U+00F1>o (Venezuela). Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> and "[[Marta (song)|Marta]]", an auto-biographical song whose [[music video]] stars [[Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez]].<ref>[http://www.prensalibre.com/escenario/espectaculos/Ricardo_Arjona-Marta-Poquita_Ropa-video_0_449355368.html "Arjona presentar<U+00E1> el video Marta protagonizado por Edith Gonz<U+00E1>lez"]. Prensa Libre.</ref> Both, like the lead single, failed to gain much airplay in the U.S., and charted poorly.

====2011<U+2013>present: ''Independiente'', Metamorfosis and world tour====
Arjona released his thirteenth studio album, ''[[Independiente (Ricardo Arjona album)|Independiente]]'', on 4 October 2011. It became his fourth number-one set on Top Latin Albums when it debuted atop the chart for the week ending 22 October; and within a week went Gold in Chile, United States and [[Mexico]]; and Platinum in Venezuela and Argentina]].<ref name=indep2>[http://musica.univision.com/noticias/article/2011-10-12/ricardo-arjona-billboard-independiente-disco-oro "Ricardo Arjona, de nuevo en la cima con 'Independiente'"]. ''Univisi<U+00F3>n M<U+00FA>sica''. Retrieved 12 October 2011.</ref> ''Independiente'' was his first release as an independent artist, appearing on his ''[[Metamorfosis]]'' label, a company he created to refocus his career.<ref name=inde501>(12-10-2011). [http://musica.univision.com/noticias/article/2011-10-12/ricardo-arjona-billboard-independiente-disco-oro "Ricardo Arjona, de nuevo en la cima con 'Independiente'"]. ''Univisi<U+00F3>n Musica''. Retrieved 15 October 2011.</ref> The album was distributed by Warner.<ref name=itunes/> ''Billboard'' noted that although other groups have decided to go independent after working with major record labels, Arjona was by far the most important artist in Latin pop to do so.<ref name=indep34>(07-07-2011). [http://www.sandiegored.com/noticias/14853/Ricardo-Arjona-sacara-un-nuevo-disco-bajo-su-propio-sello-independiente/ "Ricardo Arjona sacar<U+00E1> un nuevo disco bajo su propio sello independiente"]. ''San Diego Red''. Retrieved 30 October 2011.</ref>

{{Quote box
| quote  = "Inside the word 'Independent', even when it sounds like extreme freedom, there's a big amount of compromise and the responsibility of being able to administrate, in the best way possible, such independence."
:<U+2014>Ricardo Arjona.<ref>(04-10-2011). [http://www.el-nacional.com/noticia/3648/21/Ricardo-Arjona:-Estoy-empezando-de-nuevo-y-me-gusta.html "Ricardo Arjona: Estoy empezando de nuevo y me gusta"]. ''El Nacional'' (Venezuela). Retrieved 15-10-2011.</ref>
| width  = 25em
| align  = right
| quoted = 1
}}

The first single off ''Independiente'' was "[[El Amor (Ricardo Arjona song)|El Amor]]", released in 23 August.<ref name=itunes>[http://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/el-amor-single/id457758007?ign-mpt=uo%3D4 El Amor <U+2013> Single <U+2013>  Ricardo Arjona] ''[[iTunes]]''. Retrieved 9 October 2011.</ref> In the United States, the song reached #1 on Top Latin Songs, becoming his fourth number-one hit on that list,<ref name="TLS"/> and #1 on Latin Pop Songs.<ref name="LPS"/> It also became a hit in the rest of Latin America, reaching #1 in several countries.<ref name=latincharts1>(30-09-2011). [http://www.larazon.com.ar/show/Arjona-independiente_0_282000146.html "Un Arjona "independiente""]. ''La Raz<U+00F3>n'' (in Spanish). Retrieved 15 October 2011.</ref> The second single off the album was "[[Fuiste T<U+00FA>]]", a collaboration with Guatemalan singer [[Gaby Moreno]]. As of February 2012, the song reached the top 20 on Latin Songs, and #1 on the Latin Pop Songs.<ref name="TLS"/><ref name="LPS"/>

The [[Metamorfosis World Tour]],<ref>{{cite web| title = Ricardo Arjona comienza su Metamorfosis  | publisher=Infobae  | date = 25 January 2012  | url = http://america.infobae.com/notas/42808-Ricardo-Arjona-comienza-su-Metamorfosis
  | accessdate = 26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://ricardoarjona.com/2011/12/02/arranca-la-gira-metamorfosis-world-tour-en-enero-2012/ "ARRANCA LA GIRA <U+201C>METAMORFOSIS WORLD TOUR<U+201D> EN ENERO 2012"]. ''Ricardo Arjona Official Website''. Retrieved 16 December 2011.</ref> began on 27 January 2012 in [[Toluca]],<ref name="peralta">Peralta, Karina (14-12-2011). [http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/ad85e60f5eb11cd60e06af3916c8fe8a "Ricardo Arjona traer<U+00E1> <U+201C>Metamorfosis<U+201D> a Tampico"]. ''Milenio''. Retrieved 16 December 2011.</ref> where he he had launched all of his concert tours. The tour visited Latin America, North America and several countries in Europe.<ref name=peralta/> 

[[File:Arjona Santiago Chile 2012.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Arjona singing in [[Santiago de Chile]].]]
In 22 March 2012, a controversy surrounded a supposed [[Iran]]ian law that forbade Arjona's music,<ref name=laextra/> as disclosed by Venezuelan [[television channel]] [[Globovisi<U+00F3>n]], and other regional newspapers.<ref name="Moscatel"/><ref>SDP Noticias (22 March 2012). [http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/daranpenademuerteaquienescuchemusicadericardoarjonaeniran-1245767.html "Dar<U+00E1>n pena de muerte a quien escuche m<U+00FA>sica de Ricardo Arjona en Ir<U+00E1>n"]. La Vanguardia (Mexico). Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> This claim turned out to be false<ref>(23 March 2012). [http://www.avn.info.ve/node/104885 "Medios privados venezolanos difunden falsa informaci<U+00F3>n sobre Ir<U+00E1>n"]. Agencia Venezolana de Noticias. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> and Globovisi<U+00F3>n later issued an apology.<ref>[http://globovision.com/news.php?nid=223353 "Informaci<U+00F3>n de Ir<U+00E1>n sobre Ricardo Arjona ser<U+00ED>a producto de una broma"]. [[Globovisi<U+00F3>n]]. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> On 29 March, ''Billboard'' confirmed that Moreno had also signed with Metamorfosis.<ref name="Aguila">Aguila, Justino (29 March 2012). [http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/genre/latin/gaby-moreno-signs-with-ricardo-arjona-s-1006622152.story "Gaby Moreno Signs With Ricardo Arjona's Metamorfosis"]. Billboard. Retrieved on 30 March 2012.</ref> "When I turned 17, I was signed by a very important label in the United States, [...], but I didn't feel comfortable when they told me which songs had to go into production", the singer said in a statement.<ref name="Aguila"/> 

Between 31 March and 1 April, Arjona toured Guatemala as part of world tour. The two concerts he presented in the [[Estadio Mateo Flores|Mateo Flores stadium]] were both sellouts, making Arjona the first artist in [[History of Guatemala|Guatemalan history]] to achieve this feat.<ref>(3 April 2012). [http://entretenimiento.terra.com.pe/musica/concierto-de-ricardo-arjona-rompe-records-en-su-pais-natal,e396b98c29976310VgnVCM3000009acceb0aRCRD.html "Concierto de Ricardo Arjona rompe r<U+00E9>cords en su pa<U+00ED>s natal"]. Terra. Retrieved on 7 April 2012.</ref> On April 9, 2012, [[United States|American]] [[telecommunications]] [[corporation]] [[AT&T]] begun airing a commercial promoting the [[Nokia]] [[Lumia 900]] [[smartphone]], featuring the singer.<ref>[http://www.ricg.com/marketing_articles/digital_marketing/att_gets_multi_cultural_with_multi_channel_campaign/ "AT&T Gets Multi-cultural With Multi-channel campaign"]. RICG. Retrieved April 15, 2012.</ref> Titled "The Shoot", the spot shows how a teenage boy uses his Nokia smartphone to record Arjona's performance, and then showing it to his mother. It also features the song "Mi Novia Se Est<U+00E1> Poniendo Vieja" from the album ''Independiente'', and was released on [[Mother's Day]].<ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/consumer-empowerment-at-the-forefront-of-atts-new-ad-campaign-featuring-national-spots-on-major-spanish-language-networks-2012-04-11 "Consumer Empowerment at the Forefront of AT&T's New Ad Campaign Featuring National Spots on Major Spanish-Language Networks"]. Market Watch. Retrieved on April 16, 2012.</ref> 

As of 16 April 2012, the ''Metamorfosis World Tour'' had reached more than 400,000 fans, from which about 160,000 were just from his [[Buenos Aires]] tour dates on April 12<U+2013>15.<ref>Efe (April 16, 2012). [http://www.rpp.com.pe/2012-04-16-ricardo-arjona-rompe-record-en-buenos-aires-noticia_472538.html "Ricardo Arjona rompe record en Buenos Aires"]. RPP Noticias. Retrieved on April 18, 2012.</ref> On April 25, Arjona's show on [[Mendoza, Argentina]] had an attendance of 24,000 people, breaking the record set by [[Luis Miguel]] 10 years prior, and thus becoming the highest-grossing artist ever in that province.<ref>Trap<U+00E9>, Oscar (April 25, 2012). [http://www.diariouno.com.ar/espectaculos/Arjona-convoco-a-mas-de-24.000-personas-en-el-Estadio-Malvinas-Argentinas-20120426-0003.html "Arjona convoc<U+00F3> a m<U+00E1>s de 24.000 personas en el Malvinas Argentinas"]. Diario Uno. Retrieved on April 25, 2012.</ref> Hours before his performance on Mendoza, the [[Malvinas Argentinas]] stadium in which the concert was held, a fire burned close to one of the entries of the complex.<ref>Abraham, Leandro (April 25, 2012). [http://www.sitioandino.com/nota/34592-a-horas-del-show-de-arjona-hubo-un-importante-incendio-en-el-estadio-malvinas/ "A horas del show de Arjona, hubo un importante incendio en el estadio Malvinas"]. Sitio Andino. Retrieved on April 25, 2012.</ref>

==Artistry==
===Music and style===
[[File:Marc Anthony 2009 White House.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Marc Anthony]] sang along Arjona on the [[Salsa music|salsa version]] of "Historia de Taxi".]]
Arjona's primary musical style is [[Latin pop]]. Mainly, he sings without the help of featured or additional singers. His style varied over the years, as Arjona showed the confidence to take risks to keep his music from becoming stale. In contrast to the ballad-laden ''[[D<U+00E9>jame Decir Que Te Amo]]'', on the latter two albums Arjona experimented with a range of pop/rock styles. ''Animal Nocturno'' intersperses energetic rock songs among heartfelt ballads, and the [[instrumentation]] is heavy on guitar, synthesizer, and drums.<ref>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/animal-nocturno-r176503/review "Animal Nocturno > Review". ]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> On ''Historias'', each song is stylistically distinct and the instrumentation is varied. Around two dozen instruments were used on the album, including horns, piano and [[Hammond B-3]], and strings.<ref>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/historias-r203600/review "Historias > Review"]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> On ''[[Si El Norte Fuera El Sur]]'', he crafted a relatively low-key effort characterized by intimate songs about love, culture, and politics. Most of the songs were written in 1995 while Arjona was touring<ref name=sielnorte>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/si-el-norte-fuera-el-sur-r263457/review "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur > Review"]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> and are performed acoustically with [[Caribbean music|Caribbean]] touches. Besides a couple of rockers, the songs are fairly even in tone and tempo.<ref name=sielnorte/> 

In ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]'', Arjona explored [[Afro-Caribbean music|Afro-Caribbean]] sounds, employing traditional rhythms such as [[guaracha]], [[Bachata (music)|bachata]], [[Merengue music|merengue]], and [[Salsa music|salsa]].<ref>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/galeria-caribe-r495348/review Galeria Caribe <U+2013> Ricardo Arjona]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> On ''[[Santo Pecado]]'', Arjona explored the use of symphonic sounds on his ballads, amidst a couple of rock songs stylistically similar to those on ''[[Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros]]''.<ref>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/santo-pecado-r616342/review "Santo Pecado > Review"].  Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> This album included the song "La Nena (Bit<U+00E1>cora de un Secuetro)", in which Arjona relates the story of a girl who is kidnapped by her uncle.<ref>[http://www.eluniverso.com/2006/07/04/0001/259/87FEB244F2754937A84556C9110F842B.html "Arjona condena el secuestro en nuevo tema musical"]. El Universo. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> Then, in 2005, Arjona adopted new sounds in ''Adentro''. Gutierrez considered the instrumentation, performance, and overall sonic palette to be "minimalist" and "unassuming".<ref>Gutierrez, Evan. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/adentro-r808825/review "Adentro > Review"]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> On this album, Arjona included more Latin sounds, [[Mexican music|Mexican]] and [[Tejano music]] on "Mojado",<ref>[http://www.terra.com.mx/mujer/articulo/175210/ "Intocable y Arjona unen su talento."]. Terra (Mexico). Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> a song about immigration;<ref>[http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/317111.html "Incluye Arjona en su <U+00E1>lbum tema con Intocable"]. El Universal (Mexico). Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> [[Merengue music|merengue]] and [[Colombian music|Colombian tones]] on "Adi<U+00F3>s Melancol<U+00ED>a", and some on "No Te Cambio Por Nada".

On 2007's ''[[Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer]]'', Arjona reworked past songs to fit a new style. For example, he gave "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur" a [[ska]] beat, and performed with the aid of [[Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3>]].<ref name=qdaallmusic>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/quin-dijo-ayer-r1184550/review "Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer > Review""]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> He transformed "Historia de Taxi" into a [[Salsa music|salsa song]], with the help of American singer [[Marc Anthony]]<ref name=qdaallmusic/> and pianist [[Sergio George]],<ref>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_dijo_ayer_co190707.html "Ricardo Arjona: cuenta regresiva para la salida de <U+00BF>Qui<U+00E9>n dijo ayer?"]. ADN Mundo.  Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> who commented that "It's been interesting to work with two figures from different music worlds on the interest of making good music."<ref name="sergio">[http://www.tabascohoy.com/noticia.php?id_nota=137145 "Graban Ricardo Arjona y Marc Anthony tema a d<U+00FA>o"]. Tabasco Hoy. Retrieved on May 2, 2012.</ref> He further stated that "every time a reunion of this kind happens, it's a reason to celebrate."<ref name="sergio"/> Birchmeier commented, "While only a couple of the new versions depart stylistically from the originals, the contemporary productions breathe new life into these songs."<ref name=qdaallmusic/> "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo" was re-recorded with singer [[Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica|Sandro]]. This turned out to be the last song recorded by the latter, who died 4 January 2010.<ref name=lagaceta>[http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/359604/Espect%C3%A1culos/Hoy_respira_mejor_nunca.html "Hoy respira mejor que nunca"]. La Gaceta. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> This album included three new songs. The [[lead single]], "Qui<U+00E9>n" was written by Arjona and produced by himself and Torres.<ref name=adnmundo2>[http://www.adnmundo.com/contenidos/adncool/ricardo_arjona_quien_nuevo_disco_co100707.html "Ricardo Arjona habla de su nueva canci<U+00F3>n"]. ADN Mundo.  Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> "Quiero" and "Espantap<U+00E1>jaros" are the other two new songs on the album.

[[File:Paquita la del Barrio.jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[Paquita la del Barrio]] sang along Arjona on [[ranchera]] "Ni Tu Ni Yo".]]
''5to Piso'' is mainly driven by piano and [[String instrument|strings]].<ref name=5topisoam>Birchmeier, Jason. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/5to-piso-r1446244/review "5to Piso > Review"]. Allmusic. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> Exceptions are "La Bailarina Vecina", crafted with pure [[Orchestration|orchestral arrangements]]; and "Ni T<U+00FA> Ni Yo", a [[Ranchera|ranchera style]] song featuring [[Paquita la del Barrio]].<ref name=5topisoam/> The album also includes a song called "Que Nadie Vea", in which the artist sings about [[homosexuality]].<ref>[http://www.listindiario.com.do/entretenimiento/2009/5/29/102980/Arjona-impacta "Arjona impacta"]. Listin Diario. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> On ''5to Piso'', Arjona commented that he tried to recoup the freshness of his first albums, saying that he "tried to reconcile a little with the Ricardo Arjona from the first albums to let out some of that freshness that makes so good to the songs."<ref>[http://www.estereofonica.com/con-quinto-piso-arjona-quiere-refrescar-la-frescura-de-sus-primeros-discos/ "Con <U+2018>Quinto Piso<U+2019> Arjona quiere refrescar la frescura de sus primeros discos"]. Estereofonica. Ret. on 28 March 2012.</ref>

''[[Poquita Ropa]]'' offered a drastic change in which Arjona minimized the number of instruments. The result was a set of [[a capella]] performances. Arjona commented about this album that "music and women look better with little clothes."<ref name=unionradio1/> Production was handled by Arjona and Dan Warner, who also worked with [[Shakira]], [[Celine Dion]] and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=puente1>[http://www.nacion.com/2010-08-09/Entretenimiento/NotaPrincipal/v09-GERAR-MUSICA1.aspx "Ricardo Arjona tiende hoy su Puente"]. La Naci<U+00F3>n. Retrieved on 28 March 2012.</ref> Birchmeier gave the album a somewhat positive review, saying that it was a "stripped-down acoustic effort", considering it "impressive".<ref name="birchmeier4">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1841995|pure_url=yes}}|title= Poquita Ropa > Review| first=Jason|last=Birchmeier |publisher=Allmusic |accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref> He also commented that ''Poquita Ropa'' "finds Arjona at his most naked, backed by spare [[Musical arrangements|arrangements]] of [[acoustic guitar]], piano, and [[Hammond B-3]] along with occasional touches of [[String instrument|strings]], [[woodwinds]], and chorus vocals."<ref name="birchmeier4"/> 

{{Listen
 |filename     = Fuiste_Tu_Ricardo_Arjona.ogg
 |title        = "Fuiste T<U+00FA>"
 |description  = A sample of "Fuiste T<U+00FA>" from ''[[Independiente (Ricardo Arjona album)|Independiente]]'', displaying the first chorus sang by Arjona and Gaby Moreno.
}}
"Puente", the lead single, is the only notable exception. It lasts eight and a half minutes and is divided in three parts. The first is sung mainly with a piano. The second part is a ballad with [[Caribbean music|Caribbean]] and [[Latin music|Latin sounds]], with some [[Salsa music|salsa]] and [[Cuban music|Cuban influences]].<ref>[http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldetoluca/notas/n1739751.htm "Le canta al pueblo cubano"]. El Sol de Toluca. Retrieved on 23 March 2012.</ref> The third mixes salsa and [[Merengue music|merengue]], with Cuban influences. "Puente" resembles Arjona's work on ''[[Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe]]''.<ref name="birchmeier4"/> This album was the first since ''[[Adentro]]'', that Arjona worked without Torres. 

In ''[[Independiente (Ricardo Arjona album)|Independiente]]'', Arjona returned to his trademark sound, which Torres helped craft. David Feffries of Allmusic gave the album a somewhat positive review. He compared the production values and musical style of ''Independiente'' with those of past albums ''Animal Nocturno'' and ''Historias'', stating, "Returning fans will revel in this combination of freedom and growth, and appreciate the return of producer Tommy Torres, the man who has been behind the boards for quite a few of Arjona's most popular releases", referring precisely to the absence of Torres in the production of ''Poquita Ropa''.<ref name="feffries">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2283669|pure_url=yes}}|title= Independiente > Review| first=David|last=Jeffries |publisher=Allmusic |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref>

===Collaborators===
Only longtime collaborators Dan Warner and Tommy Torres provided notable [[background vocals]] where needed. Five Arjona albums, including one compilation album, feature additional artists. ''Galer<U+00ED>a Caribe'' features vocals from artist [[Ednita Nazario]] on "Porque Hablamos". ''Adentro'' features vocals from Spanish artist [[Chenoa]] on "Ping<U+00FC>inos En La Cama" and as well as American [[Tejano music|Tejano]] band [[Intocable]] on "Mojado". The third album, ''Qui<U+00E9>n Dijo Ayer'', features additional vocals from [[Marta S<U+00E1>nchez]] on "Tarde (Sin Da<U+00F1>os a Terceros)"; [[Pante<U+00F3>n Rococ<U+00F3>]] on "Si El Norte Fuera El Sur"; Marc Anthony on "Historia de Taxi"; [[Sandro de Am<U+00E9>rica|Sandro]] on "Realmente No Estoy Tan Solo"; and [[Eros Ramazzotti]] on "A Ti". The fourth is ''5to Piso'', on which [[Paquita la del Barrio]] collaborates on the track "Ni T<U+00FA> Ni Yo". The fifth album is ''Independiente'', in which Moreno starred alongside Arjona on "[[Fuiste T<U+00FA>]]".

